                </a></li></ul></div><p><strong>Figure 1.  <span><em>elt-2</em>(RNAi) animals are hypersusceptible to <em>S. enterica-</em>mediated killing and are colonized by <em>E. coli</em>.</span></strong></p><a id="article1.body1.sec2.sec1.fig1.caption1.p1" name="article1.body1.sec2.sec1.fig1.caption1.p1"></a><p>(<strong>A</strong>) Wild-type nematodes grown on <em>E. coli</em> carrying a vector control or on <em>E. coli</em> expressing <em>elt-2</em> double-stranded RNA were exposed to <em>S. enterica</em> SL1344 (P&lt;0.0001).</p>
<a id="article1.body1.sec2.sec1.fig1.caption1.p2" name="article1.body1.sec2.sec1.fig1.caption1.p2"></a><p>60 nematodes were used for each condition. Results are representative of at least 3 independent experiments.</p>
<a id="article1.body1.sec2.sec1.fig1.caption1.p3" name="article1.body1.sec2.sec1.fig1.caption1.p3"></a><p>(<strong>B</strong>) Wild-type nematodes grown on <em>E. coli</em> carrying a vector control or on <em>E. coli</em> expressing <em>elt-2</em> double-stranded RNA were placed on FUdR containing plates with lawns of heat-killed <em>E. coli</em> OP50 (P = 0.0011).</p>
<a id="article1.body1.sec2.sec1.fig1.caption1.p4" name="article1.body1.sec2.sec1.fig1.caption1.p4"></a><p>20 nematodes were used for each condition. Results are representative of at least 3 independent experiments.</p>
<a id="article1.body1.sec2.sec1.fig1.caption1.p5" name="article1.body1.sec2.sec1.fig1.caption1.p5"></a><p>(<strong>C</strong>) and (<strong>D</strong>) Wild-type nematodes grown on <em>E. coli</em> carrying a vector control (C) or on <em>E. coli</em> expressing <em>elt-2</em> double-stranded RNA (D) were exposed to <em>E. coli</em> expressing DSred for 24 hours, and then visualized using a Leica TCS SL spectral confocal microscope (bar = 50 µm).</p>
<a id="article1.body1.sec2.sec1.fig1.caption1.p6" name="article1.body1.sec2.sec1.fig1.caption1.p6"></a><p>(<strong>E</strong>) Wild-type nematodes grown on <em>E. coli</em> carrying a vector control or on <em>E. coli</em> expressing <em>elt-2</em> double-stranded RNA were transferred to a clean LB plate either immediately or after 24 hours exposure to <em>E. coli</em> OP50 (+24 hrs), where they were allowed to defecate for 2 hours.</p>
